â­ 3. WHEN TO USE CONSTRUCTOR vs SETTER INJECTION (VERY IMPORTANT)
âœ” Use Constructor Injection When:

The dependency is mandatory

The object cannot work without it

Good for immutability (values cannot be changed later)

Examples in real life:

Phone needs a battery

Car needs an engine

In your code:
PaymentService & DeliveryService for OrderService.

âœ” Use Setter Injection When:

The dependency is optional

OR it can be changed later

OR sometimes you don't have it at the time of object creation

Examples in real life:

Choosing UPI/Card/Cash at the time of payment

Adding a promo code (optional)

Selecting a discount coupon

In your code:
switchPaymentMethod(int choice) in PaymentService
setDiscountCode() in OrderService (if you add it later)

â­ 4. WHY BOTH ARE USED IN ZOMATO PROJECT?
âœ” PaymentService needs a default payment â†’ Constructor Injection

Because order cannot start without at least one payment method.

âœ” User may change payment method â†’ Setter-like method

Because user chooses UPI/Card at runtime.

âœ” OrderService MUST have:

PaymentService

DeliveryService
So â†’ Constructor Injection
Order cannot be created without these.

â­ Final Summary for You (16-year old level)
Injection Type	Meaning	When to Use	Example in Zomato
Constructor Injection	Must have	Object cannot exist without it	OrderService needs Payment & Delivery
Setter Injection	Optional / Changeable	Value may change later	Switch between UPI and Card
Method-based Switch	Runtime decisions	Based on user choice	Choosing payment method in console